Mulboyne noted that, humorously, Diwali in Japan features–[what
else](http://sobadsogood.com/2014/12/01/29-wonderfully-cute-and-quirky-
japanese-mascots/)?–a cute mascot representative, in this case shaped like a
piece of naan flatbread:

> My personal favourite is mascot Nan-chan
> [pic.twitter.com/nl2W3qmyr1](https://t.co/nl2W3qmyr1)
>
> — Mulboyne (@Mulboyne) [October 19,
> 2017](https://twitter.com/Mulboyne/status/920905208871321600?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw)

Mulboyne notes that Nan-chan has been around for a few years, having been
noticed by other Twitter users:

> Hard not to keep looking for more photos.
> [pic.twitter.com/n5Uw5OZ9QN](https://t.co/n5Uw5OZ9QN)
>
> — Mulboyne (@Mulboyne) [October 19,
> 2017](https://twitter.com/Mulboyne/status/920962261111390210?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw)

The Diwali celebration itself was well attended, and featured two days of
dance performances and other cultural events.

